{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox astronaut | name = Nicole Aunapu Mann | other_names = | image = Nicole Aunapu Mann portrait.jpg | image_size = | caption = | type = [[NASA]] Astronaut | nationality = American | status = Active | birth_name = Nicole Victoria Aunapu | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|6|27}} | birth_place = [[Petaluma, California]], [[US]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = | current_occupation = | previous_occupation = Test pilot | alma_mater = {{ubl|[[US Naval Academy]]|[[Stanford University]]|[[United States Naval Test Pilot School|US Naval Test Pilot School]]}} | rank = [[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]], [[USMC]] | space_time = | selection = [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|2013 NASA Group 21]] | evas = | eva_time = | missions = | insignia = | retirement = | awards = }}
'''Nicole Victoria Aunapu Mann''' (born June 27, 1977) is an American test pilot and [[NASA]] astronaut. She is an [[McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornet|F/A-18 Hornet]] pilot, and a graduate of the [[US Naval Academy]], [[Stanford University]] and the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|US Naval Test Pilot School]].<ref name="nasabio">{{cite web | last = Whiting | first = Melanie | title = Nicole A. Mann (LtCol, U.S. Marine Corps) NASA Astronaut | publisher = NASA | date = August 4, 2018 | url = https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/nicole-a-mann/biography | accessdate = October 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="spacefactsbio">{{cite web | title = Nicole Victoria Aunapu "Duke" Mann | work = Biographies of U.S. Astronauts | publisher = Spacefacts | date = April 18, 2018 | url = http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/astronauts/english/mann_nicole.htm | accessdate = October 25, 2018 }}</ref> She has over 2,500 flight hours in 25 types of aircraft, 200 carrier landings, and has flown 47 combat missions in Iraq and Afghanistan. Mann completed astronaut training in 2015, and was assigned in August 2018 to [[Boe-CFT]], the first test flight of the Boeing [[CST-100 Starliner]].<ref name=nasabio /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-s-newest-astronauts-complete-training |title=NASA's Newest Astronauts Complete Training |date=July 9, 2015 |accessdate=July 10, 2015 |publisher=NASA }}</ref><ref name=nasacc_crew>{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-assigns-crews-to-first-test-flights-missions-on-commercial-spacecraft |title=NASA Assigns Crews to First Test Flights, Missions on Commercial Spacecraft |date=August 3, 2018 |access-date=August 4, 2018 |website=NASA}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Nicole Victoria Aunapu was born on June 27, 1977 to Howard and Victoria Aunapu, and grew up in [[Penngrove, California]].<ref name=spacefactsbio /> In 1995, she graduated from [[Rancho Cotate High School]] in [[Rohnert Park, California]].<ref name=PD>{{cite news|last1=Kovner|first1=Guy|title=Nicole Aunapu Mann, Marine pilot, claims 1 of 8 NASA training slots|url=http://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/2229670-181/nicole-aunapu-mann-marine-pilot|accessdate=October 25, 2018|publisher=Santa Rosa Press Democrat|date=June 18, 2013}}</ref> Mann attended the [[US Naval Academy]], and graduated in 1999 with a Bachelor of Science degree in mechanical engineering. After [[Officer (armed forces)# Commission Sources and Training|commissioning]] in the [[US Navy]], she attended graduate school at [[Stanford University]], where she received a Master of Science degree in mechanical engineering, specializing in fluid mechanics.<ref name=nasabio />
==Military career== After completing graduate school, Mann attended [[The Basic School]], and began flight training at [[NAS Pensacola]]. She was awarded her [[United States Naval Aviator|Naval Aviator]] wings in 2002, and completed training for the [[F/A-18 Hornet]] in [[VFA-106]] at [[NAS Oceana]]. Mann joined [[VMFA-251]] at [[MCAS Beaufort]], and deployed twice on the [[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS Enterprise]] with [[CVW-1]] in support of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]] and [[Operation Enduring Freedom]]. She was a member of Class 135 at the [[U.S. Naval Test Pilot School|US Naval Test Pilot School]], and served as an F/A-18 Test Pilot in [[VX-23]] at [[NAS Patuxent River]]. At the time of her selection as an astronaut candidate, she was Joint Mission Planning System Expeditionary Integrated Product Team Lead at PMA-281.<ref name=nasabio />
==NASA career== In 2013, Man was selected as one of the eight members of [[NASA Astronaut Group 21]]. She completed her training in 2015, and has since served as a [[Northrop T-38 Talon|T-38 Talon]] Safety and Training Officer, and was the Assistant to the Chief of Exploration. She worked on development of the [[Orion spacecraft]], [[Space Launch System]], and the Exploration Ground Systems. <ref name=nasabio /><ref name=PD/><ref name="NASA">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013astroclass.html |title=2013 Astronaut Class |author=National Aeronautics and Space Administration |author-link=National Aeronautics and Space Administration |publisher=NASA |accessdate=June 19, 2013}}</ref> In August 2018 she was assigned to [[Boe-CFT]], the first test flight of the Boeing [[CST-100 Starliner]].<ref name=nasacc_dates3>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2018/08/02/nasas-commercial-crew-program-target-test-flight-dates-3/|title=NASA’s Commercial Crew Program Target Test Flight Dates|date=August 2, 2018|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref>
==Personal life== Mann and her husband, Travis, have a son, and live in [[Houston, Texas]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
== Awards == As a student at the Naval Academy, Mann played soccer, and was an Academic All American. She was a Trident Scholar, and a Distinguished Graduate. During her military career, she received two [[Air Medals]], two [[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medals]], and two [[Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medals]]. She was the Honor Graduate in her US Naval Test Pilot School class. She received the NASA 2015 Stephen D. Thorne Safety Award, and the 2017 Jerry Yeagley Award for Exceptional Personal Achievement. Mann is a member of the [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]], [[Tailhook Association]], US Naval Test Pilot School Alumni Association, United States Naval Academy Alumni Association, received the Leroy Grumman "Best Paper" Award at the East Coast Society of Experimental Test Pilots Symposium.<ref name=nasabio />
