'''Otto Liiv''' ({{osd|6 September|1905|24 August}} in [[Narva]] – 10 December 1942 in [[Tartu]]) was an Estonian historian and archivist. He was one of the founders of Estonian archival science as well as one of the most prolific and respected historians in Estonia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Tiit |last2= |first2= |year=1987 |title=Ajaloolane ja arhivaar Otto Liiv Tartu Ülikooli õppejõuna |journal=Issues in the History of the University of Tartu |publisher=Tartu University |volume= XIX |issue= |pages=48–55 |url= |doi= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pillak |first1=Peep |last2= |first2= |year=1996 |title=Otto Liiv 1905-1942 : bibliograafia |journal=Artiklite kogumik Eesti Ajalooarhiivi 75. aastapäevaks |volume=1 |issue=8 |pages=63–78 |publisher=Eesti Ajalooarhiiv |doi= |url=http://rahvusarhiiv.ra.ee/public/TUNA/Artiklid_Biblio/PeppPillak_Otto_Liiv_TUNA2005_4.pdf |accessdate= }}</ref>
Liiv attended school in Narva and [[Tallinn]] and enrolled at the [[University of Tartu]] in 1923 and graduated in 1927. He was the head of the [[National Archives of Estonia|Estonian State Central Archives]] from 1929 to 1942. He also lectured at the University of Tartu and was the chief editor of the journal "Ajalooline Ajakiri". Liiv had an academic interest in the history of the 17th century Estonia and contributed to the books ''"The Economic History of Estonia"'' in 1937 and the third volume of ''"History of Estonia"'' in 1940.
In 2005, [[Eesti Post]] issued a commemorative [[Stamp cancellation]] marking the 100th anniversary of Otto Liiv's birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post.ee/?id=2322&prod_id=812 |title=Birth centenary of Otto Liiv, PhD |author=Lembit Lõhmus |date=06.09.2005 |work= |publisher=[[Eesti Post]] |accessdate=4 February 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129141027/http://www.post.ee/?id=2322&prod_id=812 |archivedate=January 29, 2006 }}</ref>
